## Start

```bash
jgo doctor
jgo generate
jgo run --config configs/local.yaml
```

`jgo new` creates an empty service skeleton: it does not invent an Echo or Greeter business API. `jgo generate` reconciles local HTTP/protobuf contracts and external RPC bindings. It succeeds as a no-op when none exist.

Operational endpoints use the dedicated management listener (`:9091` locally):

```text
GET /healthz  process liveness only
GET /readyz   required dependency readiness
GET /metrics  Prometheus metrics
```

Local gRPC Reflection is enabled in `configs/local.yaml`; the framework default is disabled. Server TLS/mTLS, OTLP tracing/metrics, client readiness and RPC client TLS are configuration-driven. YAML decoding is strict.
{{if .HasWeb}}

## HTTP APIs

Define complex structs under `api/http/model`, then add RPC-style HTTP APIs:

```bash
jgo api add GetUser --method GET --path /get_user \
  --request uid:int64:required:query \
  --response-data UserInfo
jgo api generate
```

Responses use `{"code":0,"msg":"","data":...}`. HTTP status and business code are separate.
{{end}}
{{if .HasGRPC}}

## Local protobuf contracts

The project starts without a `.proto` file. Add a local Service and Method only when this project owns a contract:

```bash
jgo pb service add UserService
jgo pb method add GetUser --service UserService
# Edit request fields and response business fields from field number 3.
jgo pb generate
```

The first Service defaults to package `{{.PackageName}}.v1`; use `--package company.user.v1` to choose or create another package. Install Buf tools once per Go environment only when local contracts exist:

```bash
jgo tools install
jgo pb lint
jgo pb breaking --against '.git#branch=main'
```

## Shared protobuf bindings

Bind an entire Service from a published protocol module:

```bash
jgo rpc server bind UserService --module example.com/company-api@v0.1.0
jgo rpc client bind UserService --module example.com/company-api@v0.1.0 --name user
```

For an unpublished module present in the active `go.work`, omit `@version`. An explicit version resolves released source or a matching `go.mod replace`, never unpublished workspace source. Repeating `bind` updates a compatible module version. `unbind` permanently removes a project role/dependency; it does not edit the shared protocol.
{{end}}

## Errors, logs and security

Declare business codes in `internal/errcode/catalog.go`; the catalog rejects duplicate codes/names and owns RPC-code-to-HTTP-status mapping. Add authentication and authorization adapters in the user-owned `internal/securityx/security.go` hook.

Use context-aware structured logs:

```go
logx.InfoCtx(ctx, "operation completed", "uid", uid)
logx.ErrorCtx(ctx, "operation failed", "uid", uid, "err", err)
```

Run `jgo list` for HTTP APIs, local protobuf methods, external servers and external clients. Contracts and `.jgo/rpc.json` are the source of truth.
